❯ given i have a region in the mantle where the compaction occurs how would i   
  implement this kinematically                                                  

● Let me look at a few more pieces of the code to understand how your
  surface/topography is tracked before giving you the implementation plan.

  Searched for 3 patterns, read 4 files (ctrl+o to expand)

● Now I have the full picture. The implementation path is clear because your
  existing topography system already has an exact analogue of what you need.

  ---
  The Key Insight: You Already Have the Pattern

  Look at advect_vertically_using_extrusion! (AdvectionTools.jl:225-239). It:
  1. Reads a pre-computed thickness from gridt[7, i]
  2. Converts it to a velocity: thickness / timestep
  3. Moves the topo node upward (subtracts velocity, since y is positive
  downward)

  Subsidence from melt extraction is the same pattern in reverse — a thickness
  computed from the extracted volume, applied as a downward displacement to topo
   nodes over the drainage basin.

  ---
  The Core Formula

  In 2D, everything has units of area (m²), not volume (m³). For drainage basin
  i:

  V_extracted [m²] = nmarkers_magma_mantle × mxstep × mystep

  Δh_subsidence [m] = V_extracted / (xend_drainage[i] - xstart_drainage[i])

  This is the uniform average subsidence distributed over the full basin width.
  For each topo node j whose x-position falls within [xstart_drainage[i], 
  xend_drainage[i]]:

  gridt[2, j] += Δh_subsidence        # downward (y positive downward)

  Or equivalently as a velocity:

  v_sub [m/s] = Δh_subsidence / timestep
  gridt[2, j] += v_sub * timestep

  These are identical. The direct displacement form is cleaner here.

  ---
  The Net Surface Signal

  The two effects at each topo node:

  ┌────────────┬──────────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┐
  │   Effect   │          Direction           │          Source           │
  ├────────────┼──────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ Subsidence │ gridt[2, i] += Δh_sub (down) │ mantle volume extracted   │
  ├────────────┼──────────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────┤
  │ Uplift     │ gridt[2, i] -= Δh_ext (up)   │ extrusion volume emplaced │
  └────────────┴──────────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────┘

  The extrusion uplift is already computed per drainage basin
  (extrusion_volumes[i]). The subsidence is the total extracted volume
  (nmarkers_magma_mantle × marker_area), which includes both the intrusive and
  volcanic portions. So:

  Δh_sub = (nmarkers_magma_mantle * mxstep * mystep) / basin_width   [total
  mantle loss]
  Δh_ext = extrusion_volume_m3 / injection_width                      [surface
  gain]
  Net    = Δh_sub - Δh_ext                                            [positive
  = net subsidence]

  Note that Δh_sub > Δh_ext always, because extrusions are typically 10–30% of
  total extracted volume. The rest goes into the intrusive body at depth. So the
   net effect is subsidence over the basin, with reduced subsidence near the
  eruption axis where extrusion uplift partially compensates.

  ---
  Where Each Piece Lives

  extract_melt_in_drainage_basins!          ← compute Δh_sub here
      │                                       using nmarkers_magma_mantle
      │                                       store per-basin in a new array
      │
      └── per-basin loop → also compute Δh_ext from extrusion_volumes
                            already computed here

  Topography.update_topography_using_velocity_field!
      │
      └── TopoTypeManager.topography_advect!
              │
              ├── advect_vertically_using_stokes_velocity!    (dynamic
  subsidence)
              ├── advect_vertically_using_extrusion!          (volcanic uplift)
              └── [new] advect_vertically_using_extraction_subsidence!   ← add
  here

  The subsidence thickness needs to be stored somewhere accessible to the
  topography module. The natural home is either:
  - A new row in gridt (e.g., gridt[8, i], analogous to gridt[7, i] for
  extrusion)
  - A dedicated array in your extraction model data container, passed into the
  topography step

  ---
  Spatial Distribution Options

  Option 1 — Uniform over drainage basin (simplest)

  Every topo node in [xstart_drainage[i], xend_drainage[i]] gets the same
  Δh_sub. This is the approximation that the entire basin floor subsides
  uniformly. It's reasonable when the PMZ is roughly uniform under the basin.

  Option 2 — Column-by-column (more accurate)

  For each x-column in the grid, count how many markers were actually converted
  to magma from that column and compute a local subsidence:
  Δh_sub(x_j) = n_converted_in_column_j × mxstep × mystep / dx_topo
  This requires tracking which markers were converted during the extraction
  loop, but gives a spatially varying subsidence that mirrors the actual PMZ
  geometry. For a spreading center, this would give maximum subsidence directly
  above the deepest/widest part of the melt column and taper toward the basin
  edges — which is more realistic.

  ---
  Sign Convention Check

  Your model uses y positive downward. Confirming:

  - advect_vertically_using_extrusion! subtracts velocity_y_extrusion → moves
  node upward (smaller y) → uplift ✓
  - Subsidence should add a positive velocity → moves node downward (larger y) ✓
  - gridt[2, i] += Δh_sub directly increases y → subsidence ✓

  ---
  What This Avoids

  This approach:
  - Does not touch RC1 in the Stokes solver — no pressure blowup
  - Does not require modifying the base velocity BC
  - Works entirely through the existing topography advection framework
  - Is consistent with your existing extraction scheme (melt removed = marker
  conversion counted = volume known)
  - Naturally couples with the extrusion uplift you already compute

  The one thing it does not capture is the dynamic pressure signal from
  compaction (i.e., the transient overpressure in the compaction zone). For a
  ridge model, that's typically a second-order effect on the surface topography
  compared to the direct volume budget, so this kinematic approach gives you the
   dominant signal.

