❯ the problem is that if i inpose a subsidence i have to adjust all the the     
  rock markers below the topography. help me thonk through this                 

● This is a fundamental insight. Let me think through the geometry with you
  carefully before suggesting anything.

  ---
  The Physical Picture

  When the mantle compacts at the PMZ, the overlying column doesn't just drop at
   the surface — the entire rock column above the compaction zone translates 
  downward rigidly by Δh_sub. The seafloor drops because the rock it's sitting
  on sank, not because water drained in from above.

  Before extraction:
    [sticky water              ]  y < y_topo
    [oceanic crust             ]  y_topo < y < y_moho
    [lithospheric mantle       ]  y_moho < y < y_pmz_top
    [  PMZ  ← extraction here ]  y > y_pmz_top

  After extraction (correct physics):
    [sticky water                  ]  y < y_topo + Δh_sub
    [oceanic crust  (shifted down) ]
    [lithospheric mantle (shifted) ]
    [depleted residue              ]  (PMZ compacted here)

  So yes — moving only gridt is wrong. Every marker from the surface down to the
   top of the PMZ needs to shift down by Δh_sub. You've correctly identified the
   problem.

  ---
  Why Explicit Marker Manipulation Is the Wrong Tool

  Iterating over every marker and adding Δh_sub to its y-coordinate is:

  1. Potentially double-counting: The Stokes solver already computes a velocity
  field that includes some downward flow above the depletion zone (in response
  to the density change from extraction). Adding a separate displacement on top
  of that overcounts the signal.
  2. Bypassing the advection framework: The whole point of a marker-in-cell
  method is that the velocity field moves markers. Manually shifting markers
  breaks that contract.
  3. Hard to bound: The transition from "column that subsides" to "column that
  doesn't" is not a sharp boundary — the compaction signal diffuses upward
  through the mantle.

  ---
  The Clean Kinematic Solution: Correct the Velocity Field, Not the Markers

  Instead of moving markers directly, add the subsidence as a correction to the 
  Stokes velocity field before marker advection. The existing advection
  machinery then naturally carries every marker downward by the right amount.

  The operation is:

  After Stokes solve, before marker advection:

  vy[i, j] += v_sub    for all velocity nodes above the PMZ
                        within the basin x-extent

  where:

  v_sub = Δh_sub / Δt   [m/s, positive = downward in y-positive-down convention]

  This is applied to the vy staggered grid array (vy1) — the same array used for
   marker advection. The result:

  - Every marker above the PMZ within the basin is carried downward by v_sub × 
  Δt = Δh_sub
  - gridt nodes are advected by the same corrected velocity and drop by Δh_sub
  - FlattenDensity sees the new density distribution (markers moved, density
  interface moved)
  - The Stokes solver in the next timestep gets a self-consistent density field
  - No explicit marker iteration, no RC1 changes, no BC modifications during the
   solve

  ---
  The Depth Extent of the Correction

  The correction should taper to zero at the top of the PMZ, not at the model
  base. Below the PMZ, the mantle is not participating in the column subsidence
  — it is the source of the compaction.

  v_sub(y) = Δh_sub / Δt    for y < y_pmz_top   (above PMZ)
  v_sub(y) = 0               for y ≥ y_pmz_top   (at or within PMZ)

  This also avoids conflict with your base inflow BC — the base boundary is well
   below y_pmz_top, so the correction never reaches it.

  ---
  How This Differs from the RC1 Approach

  ┌────────────────┬────────────────────────┬───────────────────────────────┐
  │                │  RC1 compaction term   │     Post-Stokes velocity      │
  │                │                        │          correction           │
  ├────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
  │ Where applied  │ Inside Stokes solve    │ After Stokes solve, before    │
  │                │ (RHS)                  │ advection                     │
  ├────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
  │ Effect on      │ Drives large pressure  │ None                          │
  │ pressure       │ gradients              │                               │
  ├────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
  │ BC conflict    │ Yes — base vy is fixed │ No — base BC not in play      │
  ├────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
  │ Column         │ Implicit via Stokes    │ Explicit, controlled          │
  │ movement       │                        │                               │
  ├────────────────┼────────────────────────┼───────────────────────────────┤
  │ Magnitude      │ φ/Δt × η — can be huge │ Δh_sub / Δt — bounded by      │
  │ control        │                        │ extraction volume             │
  └────────────────┴────────────────────────┴───────────────────────────────┘

  ---
  The One Remaining Concern

  The Stokes velocity already includes some downward signal above the extraction
   zone from the density change. When you add the kinematic correction on top,
  you could slightly overcount.

  In practice this matters very little because the subsidence velocity (Δh_sub /
   Δt) is roughly 1–10% of the spreading velocity, so the fractional error is
  small and the Stokes solver self-corrects on the next step. But if you want to
   be precise, you can compute the Stokes-driven downward displacement over the
  same column and subtract it before applying the kinematic correction:

  v_correction = v_sub - mean(vy_stokes over column above PMZ)

  This ensures you're only adding what the Stokes solver missed — the
  compaction-driven component — not the gravity/density-driven component it
  already computed.

